revision.text:
'''AbhibhƒÅvayatana''' ({{lang-sa|AbhibhvƒÅyatana}}, {{lang-pi|AbhibhƒÅyatana}}), or '''abhibhƒÅyatana''' ({{lang-sa|AbhibhƒÅyatana}},<ref name="oxford">{{cite encyclopedia|title=AbhibhƒÅvayatana|encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of World Religions|year=1997|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref> {{lang-pi|AbhibhƒÅyƒÅtana}}, "control of perceptions"),<ref name="oxford"/><ref name="eb">{{cite encyclopedia|title=AbhibhvƒÅyatana|encyclopedia=Encyclop√¶dia Britannica|year=2009|accessdate=May 2, 2009|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1239/abhibhvayatana}}</ref> is a concept in [[Buddhism]] through which [[meditation]] is achieved in eight stages by mastering the senses.<ref name="eb"/> During this process, the practitioner separates himself from the physical world, frees himself from attachments to physical forms, and begins freeing himself from [[suffering|pain]] and [[pleasure]] of the material world tied to [[dukkha|suffering in Buddhism]].<ref name="eb"/>
The eight stages of abhibhƒÅvayatana are:<ref name="oxford"/>
# Mastery of perception of the form of one's own body and limited forms beyond it # Mastery of perception of the form of one's own body, and of forms beyond it # Mastery of perception of formlessness in relation to one's own body and limited forms beyond it # Mastery of perception of formlessness in relation to one's own body and the whole world beyond it # Mastery of perception over different forms of [[beauty]] (stages 5‚Äì8)
