{{About|the person mentioned in the [[Book of Mormon]]|the distant ancestor of [[Jesus Christ]]|Amminadab}}
:''For the Israeli village, see [[Aminadav]].''
{{Religious text primary|date=October 2011}}
According to the [[Book of Mormon]], '''Aminadab''' ({{IPAc-en|…ô|Àà|m|…™|n|…ô|d|√¶|b}})<ref>[http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng LDS.org: "Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), [[Wikipedia:IPA for English|IPA]]-ified from ¬´a-mƒ≠n¬¥a-dƒÉb¬ª</ref> was a [[Nephite]] who fell away from the church, and became associated with the [[Lamanites]].<ref>{{lds|Helaman|hel|5|34|41}}</ref>

In the [[Book of Helaman]], after [[Nephi, son of Helaman|Nephi]] abdicated the Chief Judgment Seat to [[Cezoram]], he and his brother [[Lehi, son of Helaman|Lehi]] went to preach to the Lamanites, who imprison them.

==Lamanite prisons==
One day, [[angels]] came and wrapped Nephi and Lehi in fire, while darkness surrounded the people. The guards were confused, and Aminadab told them to repent. The text implies the guard prayed in faith, had his body encircled with fire, and converted. Aminadab's testimony helped to convert three hundred Lamanites who witnessed the events.

