[[File:Aeneas Erects a Tomb to his Nurse, Caieta, and Flees the Country of Circe (Aeneid, Book VII) MET DT10857.jpg|thumb|Aeneas Erects a Tomb to his Nurse, Caieta, and Flees the Country of Circe (Aeneid, Book VII)]] In [[Roman mythology]], '''Caieta''' was the [[wet-nurse]] of [[Aeneas]]. The Roman poet [[Virgil|Vergil]] locates her grave on the bay at [[Gaeta]], to which she also gives her name (''cf.'' [[Caietae Portus]]).<ref>[[Virgil|Vergil]] ''[[Aeneid]]'' 7.1-4</ref> The poet [[Ovid]], working a generation later, provides an epitaph: ::HIC ‚Ä¢ ME ‚Ä¢ CAIETAM ‚Ä¢ NOTAE ‚Ä¢ PIETATIS ‚Ä¢ ALVMNUS ::EREPTAM ‚Ä¢ ARGOLICO ‚Ä¢ QVO ‚Ä¢ DEBVIT ‚Ä¢ IGNE ‚Ä¢ CREMAVIT<ref>[[Ovid]] ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' 14.443-444</ref> "Here me, Caieta, snatched from Grecian flames, my pious son consumed with fitting fire."<ref>[[Ovid]], ''Metamorphoses'', trans. Frank Justus Miller, [[Loeb Classical Library]] 43 (Cambridge, MA: [[Harvard University Press]], 1984), 331.</ref> The fourth-century commentator [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]] writes that there was some controversy about whose wet-nurse Caieta was: in addition to Aeneas, he offers [[Creusa#Creusa_in_Virgil.27s_Aeneid|Creusa]] and [[Ascanius]] as possibilities.<ref>[[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]] ''In Vergili Aeneidem Commentarii'' 7.1</ref>
