{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}} {{Infobox religious building | name = Seitenky≈´ | native_name = | image = Sakado Xientengong Tenmon 20110203 1.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Main gate to Seitenky≈´ | map_type = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = 51-1 Tsukagoshi, Sakado-shi, Saitama-ken | coordinates = | religious_affiliation = Taoism | deity = Dosso Sanqing | country = Japan | functional_status = | website = {{URL|www.seitenkyu.com}} | founded_by = | year_completed = 1995 }} {{Nihongo|'''Seitenky≈´'''|ËÅñÂ§©ÂÆÆ}} (Chinese: ''Xien Ten Gong'' or ''Sheng Tian Gong'') is a Taiwanese style [[Taoist]] temple in [[Sakado, Saitama]], Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://japantourist.jp/view/sheng-tian-gong-temple-seitenkyu|title= Sheng Tian Gong, Japan's largest Taoist temple in Taiwanese tradition|first= Todd |last= Wojnowski|date= 21 August 2012 |work= Japan Tourist|publisher= Japan Partnership K.K.|location= Tokyo, Japan|archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate= 10 February 2013}}</ref> It is the largest Taoist temple in Japan.<ref name="koedonet">{{cite web |url= http://www.koedo.org/news/20673.html|script-title=ja:Âú∞Âüü„Éã„É•„Éº„ÇπÔºö„ÄÄËÅñÂ§©ÂÆÆ|trans-title=Local News: Seitenky≈´|date= 3 December 2009|publisher= Koedo Net|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate= 17 August 2011}}</ref>
==Features== It took 15 years to build this temple.<ref name=Point>{{Cite web|url=http://platz.jp/~seitennkyuu/jikuu.html|accessdate= 17 August 2011| publisher= Official website|title =Points of Interest|language= Japanese}}</ref> The temple has been built with yellow roof tiles which are exclusively used only for building temples and for housing Emperors. The ceiling in the temple is made of glass of ten thousand pieces. One stone pillar in particular which is 5 m tall is carved from a single piece and the door is 4 m wide.<ref name=Point/>
God [[Dosso Sanqing]], the main deity is worshipped in the temple. The main hall in the temple is built without any nails and has numerous impressive sculptures. Carvings on the stone pillars of five meters height are elaborate and called the [[Yin and yang|Yin]] "Ssangyong pillars". A drum tower to the left of the temple was added later, which offers views of the surroundings.<ref name="koedonet"/>
==Worship== Prayers are offered daily at the temple with incense burning. The shape and colour of incense smoke are closely observed as it portends significant omens; formations of "Dragon" "Women", "Phoenix‚Äù are said to auger well for the devotee offering prayers.<ref name=worship>{{Cite web|url=http://platz.jp/~seitennkyuu/sannpai.html|title= Good luck and God worship worship worship worship marks authentic Taiwan Charm|accessdate= 17 August 2011| publisher= Official website| language= Japanese }}</ref> Devotees also offer prayers with talismans in different shrines of the temple complex, depending on their year of birth, of specific colour seeking fulfillment of their desires.<ref name="koedonet"/>
