'''Surkhab I''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: ÿ≥Ÿáÿ±ÿßÿ®) was the second ruler of the [[Bavand dynasty]] from ca. 673 to 717. 

He was the son of [[Farrukhzad]], a [[Parthia]]n nobleman from the [[House of Ispahbudhan|Ispahbudhan family]], a family which had a long story of service to the [[Sasanians]], tracing his descent back to [[Bawi]]. Surkhab also had four brothers named [[Isfandyadh]], Shahram, Bahram, and Farrukhan. In 665, Farrukhzad was murdered by an [[House of Karen|Karenid]] named [[Valash]], who then had his domains conquered. After the murder of his father, Surkhab fled to a Bavand stronghold in [[Mazandaran]]. In 673, Surkhab avenged his father by killing Valash, and then reconquered lost Bavand territory. He then crowned himself as ''[[ispahbadh]]'' of the Bavandids at his capital in [[Farim, Iran|Perim]]. Surkhab died in 717, and was succeeded by his son [[Mihr Mardan]].

